## Refutation / known limits
- The examples have NOT been executed against a live hegel-core
  server. They are syntactically valid Scheme, follow the existing
  example convention, and use only the public (hegel) API
  (define-hegel-test, tc-draw, integers, lists-of, text). But
  hegel-guile's protocol layer is currently in a refuted state
  (see hegel-guile-2 through 7) so a live run blocks on protocol
  fixes that are not in scope here.
- The .beads/issues.jsonl edits were made by hand-appending JSON
  lines because bd init fails (dolt name dash). When that bug is
  fixed, bd will pick up issues 8-11 from the JSONL automatically.
- The file-roundtrip cage assumes /tmp/ is writable. CI runners
  on locked-down environments may not have a writable /tmp/.
- I did NOT modify .beads/.gitignore or .gitignore even though bd
  init had silently rewritten them — those changes are out of
  scope for this commit and should be reviewed by the maintainer
  separately.

## Meta - research / context / deep-dives
- Three more sage PBT cages are listed in
  docs/property-cages-from-sage.md as future cross-pollination
  candidates: telemetry counter normalisation, model fallback
  selection, OTLP {} sentinel encoding. Worth porting when the
  hegel-guile ecosystem grows enough to need them.
- Worth a future deep-dive: a hegel-guile harness that runs the
  sage PBT properties via hegel's CBOR protocol instead of sage's
  ad-hoc LCG. Would give sage real Hypothesis-backed shrinking
  with no code changes to sage itself — just a different test
  runner.
- The bd JSONL append pattern is interesting: when bd is broken
  but the JSONL is intact, you can still file issues by appending
  lines. The JSONL format is stable and forward-compatible. Worth
  documenting as a fallback in the bd README.
- Open question: should hegel-guile's CONTRIBUTING.md mention the
  cross-pollination convention so other projects know how to
  contribute property cages? Probably yes once the protocol layer
  stabilises.
